---
alwaysApply: true
---

Every development phase that introduces new database entities must also implement development seed data.

Seed data is part of the implementation, not an optional task.

Requirements

• Create idempotent seed scripts.
• Running the seed multiple times must never create duplicate records.
• Seed data must be realistic and production-like.
• Maintain proper relationships and referential integrity.
• Organize seeds by module/domain.
• Support resetting and reseeding the development database.
• Use deterministic data where practical.
• Never execute development seeds in production.

Every new entity introduced during a phase must have representative seed data.

Seed data should support:

- UI development
- Manual testing
- API testing
- Integration testing
- End-to-end testing
- Demonstrations

Provide commands for:

- Seed database
- Reset database
- Clear database
- Reseed database

Document all commands.

Whenever database models change:

- Update seed scripts.
- Update documentation.
- Keep seeds synchronized with schema changes.

Testing should use seeded data whenever appropriate.

Before completing a phase, verify that the entire application functions correctly using only seeded data.
